We all write using every day. Very few of us stop to think about what it actually does.
Most of us have written code like this thousands of times:
using (var connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
{
connection.Open();
// Do work
}It works.
The connection closes.
Life is good.
Until one day production throws:
The timeout period elapsed prior to obtaining a connection from the pool.Or a file stays locked.
Or memory usage quietly climbs all day until the application needs a restart.
Despite looking like different problems, they often have the same root cause:
“Something implemented IDisposable, and it wasn't disposed—or it was disposed incorrectly.”
Let’s clear that up once and for all.

What IDisposable Is Actually For
Many developers carry this mental model:
“The Garbage Collector cleans up my objects, so I don’t need to worry.”
That’s only partially true.
The GC manages managed memory.
It does not manage operating system resources like:

• Database connections

• File handles

• Network sockets

• Native memory

• Window handles
Those resources live outside the .NET managed heap.
The GC has no idea when your application is finished using them.
That’s why IDisposable exists.
“It provides deterministic cleanup of resources that the Garbage Collector cannot manage.”
Calling Dispose() tells the object:
“I’m finished using you. Release your unmanaged resources immediately.”

Why You Can’t Just Wait for the GC
Consider this method:
public string ReadConfig()
{
var reader = new StreamReader("config.json");
return reader.ReadToEnd();
}Will it eventually work? Yes.
Eventually the GC will collect StreamReader.
The problem is this word: Eventually.
The Garbage Collector runs based on memory pressure — not because a file handle or SQL connection needs to be released.
That means:

• Files may remain locked

• SQL connections stay in the pool

• Sockets remain open

• Native resources continue to accumulate
Waiting for the GC isn’t a cleanup strategy.
It’s simply waiting.

using Guarantees Cleanup
This is where using comes in.
using (var reader = new StreamReader("config.json"))
{
return reader.ReadToEnd();
}Behind the scenes, the compiler generates something very similar to:
var reader = new StreamReader("config.json");
try
{
return reader.ReadToEnd();
}
finally
{
reader?.Dispose();
}That finally block is the important part.
It executes even if:

• An exception is thrown

• The method returns early

• Execution leaves the block unexpectedly
In other words:
“using guarantees that Dispose() is called.”

Modern C# Makes It Even Cleaner
Since C# 8, you can use a using declaration instead.
using var connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString);
using var command = connection.CreateCommand();
connection.Open();No additional nesting.
Same guarantee.
Cleaner code.

A Resource Leak We’ve All Written
A common example looks like this:
public byte[] Render()
{
var bitmap = new Bitmap(800, 600);
var graphics = Graphics.FromImage(bitmap);
// Draw...
return ToBytes(bitmap);
}Both Bitmap and Graphics implement IDisposable.
Neither is disposed.
Over time, GDI handles accumulate until the process eventually fails.
The fix is straightforward:
public byte[] Render()
{
using var bitmap = new Bitmap(800, 600);
using var graphics = Graphics.FromImage(bitmap);
// Draw...
return ToBytes(bitmap);
}A simple rule has served me well:
“If you created an IDisposable object, you're responsible for disposing it.”

Writing Your Own IDisposable
In many cases, implementing IDisposable is surprisingly simple.
If your class only owns other managed disposable objects:
public sealed class ReportGenerator : IDisposable
{
private readonly SqlConnection _connection;
private readonly StreamWriter _output; public void Dispose()
{
_connection.Dispose();
_output.Dispose();
}
}
Notice the class is sealed.
That means you don’t need the full inheritance-aware dispose pattern.
If your class directly owns unmanaged resources, prefer SafeHandle instead of raw pointers whenever possible.

Async Resources Need Async Disposal
Some cleanup operations are asynchronous.
For those, .NET provides IAsyncDisposable.
await using var stream =
new FileStream("data.bin", FileMode.Create);
await stream.WriteAsync(buffer);await using allows cleanup without blocking a thread.

The Dependency Injection Trap
One of the easiest mistakes to make is disposing objects you don’t own.
In ASP.NET Core:
public class OrderService
{
private readonly AppDbContext _db; public OrderService(AppDbContext db)
{
_db = db;
}
}
AppDbContext was created by the DI container.
The container will dispose it automatically.
Wrapping _db in a using block will often lead to:
ObjectDisposedExceptionThe opposite mistake is just as dangerous.
Capturing a transient disposable inside a singleton can keep that object alive until the application shuts down.
A useful rule to remember is:
“If you created it with new, you dispose it. If the DI container created it, let the container dispose it.”

Things Worth Remembering
IDisposable does:

• Release unmanaged resources deterministically

• Work seamlessly with using

• Ensure cleanup even when exceptions occur

• Integrate with ASP.NET Core dependency injection
IDisposable does not:

• Free managed memory

• Replace the Garbage Collector

• Automatically dispose forgotten objects

• Mean you should dispose injected services
This still compiles — and still leaks resources:
var connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString);
connection.Open();The compiler won’t warn you.

Final Thoughts
IDisposable isn't really about memory.
It’s about ownership.
It’s about knowing who is responsible for releasing resources — and doing it at the right time.
Three simple rules prevent most resource leaks in .NET:

• If you create an IDisposable, wrap it in using.

• If your class owns unmanaged resources, prefer SafeHandle (or implement the full dispose pattern when necessary).

• If the DI container created the object, don’t dispose it yourself.
Understanding these three ideas will save you from countless connection leaks, locked files, and late-night production incidents.
The next time you typeusing, you'll know exactly why it's there.
Do you have ideas or questions? Let me know in the comments.
Thanks for reading — and happy coding! 🚀
